A browser-oriented parser generator is attractive when the grammar and runtime must ship to every editor tab. A small grammar fragment has the shape:

```text
@top SourceFile { item* }
item { Function | Struct }
Function { "fn" identifier ParamList Block }
ParamList { "(" list<Param, ",">? ")" }
Expression { identifier | number | Expression operator Expression }
```

The important API pattern is incremental rather than syntactic: `new_tree = parser.parse(new_text, old_tree, changed_ranges)`. The old tree carries enough position information for the parser to reuse unaffected subtrees. A new language can treat this as an editor contract: every keystroke updates syntax cheaply and produces a tree even when the file is invalid.
